==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hieroglyphic
<hw>Hi`er*o*glyph"ic</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>hi⟦eacute⟧roglyphe</ets>. See <er>Hieroglyphic</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sacred character; a character used in picture
writing, as of the ancient Egyptians, Mexicans, etc. Specifically, in
the plural, the picture writing of the ancient Egyptian priests. It is
made up of three, or, as some say, four classes of characters: first,
the <xex>hieroglyphic</xex> proper, or figurative, in which the
representation of the object conveys the idea of the object itself;
second, the <xex>ideographic</xex>, consisting of symbols representing
ideas, not sounds, as an ostrich feather is a symbol of truth; third,
the <xex>phonetic</xex>, consisting of symbols employed as syllables of
a word, or as letters of the alphabet, having a certain sound, as a hawk
represented the vowel <it>a.</it></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any character or figure which has, or is supposed to
have, a hidden or mysterious significance; hence, any unintelligible or
illegible character or mark.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></p>

<p><ent>Hieroglyphical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Hieroglyphic</ent>⟦br⟧
